player.seasonOutlook: Jones was selected by the Patriots with the 15th pick of April's draft. The 6-foot-3, 217-pound Alabama product is fresh off an elite 2020 campaign in which he completed 77% of 402 pass attempts and posted an 11.1 YPA and 96 total QBR (all were best in this year's class). Oh, and he threw 41 TDs to go along with four INTs. Jones is super poised and accurate, but arm strength and a lack of mobility (35 carries, 14 yards in 2020) are concerns. The latter is going to be extremely detrimental to Jones' fantasy appeal both short and long term. Cam Newton remains the favorite to start in Week 1, but it's likely Jones will make some starts this season. Of course, even if he does start, he'll be no more than a back-end QB2.

Following yet another injury-plagued season, Garoppolo is no longer the quarterback of the future in San Francisco. The 49ers drafted Trey Lance with the third overall pick in April, which means it's only a matter of time until the 29-year-old incumbent is sent to the bench. Even if Garoppolo is under center to open 2021 (which is the expectation), there isn't much weekly fantasy appeal here. Back in 2019, Garoppolo appeared in all 16 regular season games for the first time in his career and ranked top-5 in pass TDs (27), completion rate (69%) and YPA (8.4). However, low pass volume (19th in attempts) and minimal rushing contributions allowed him a career-high 14th place finish in fantasy points. Garoppolo should only be drafted in two-QB leagues.

Snell has spent his first two NFL seasons backing up James Conner, which has led to only the occasional carry most weeks, but also a handful of spot starts. In total, the 2019 fourth-round pick is averaging an ugly 3.63 YPC (1.64 YAC) on 219 career attempts and has been a non-factor as a receiver (84 yards on 19 career targets). Snell quietly racked up 13 carries inside the 5-yard line last season (seventh-most), but converted the heavy usage into only four TDs. Snell's best career weekly fantasy finish was a 14th this past season and the combination of minimal passing-game work and shaky rushing efficiency will make him an uninspiring fantasy option even if called on to start. The 23-year-old will back up first-round pick Najee Harris this season and doesn't need to be drafted.

Watson has finished as a top-5 fantasy QB each of the past three seasons and it could have been four if not for an injury as a rookie in 2017. The dual-threat athlete has ranked in the top 6 among QBs in rushing yards each of the past three seasons, while adding 15 TDs with his legs along the way. Watson's passing ability continues to improve, as he paced the NFL in passing yards (4,823) and YPA (8.9), while posting a 33-to-7 TD-to-INT mark. The 25-year-old's off-field issues leave his NFL future in doubt and, even if he plays, his supporting cast ranks among the league's worst. Watson is a strong QB1 when active, but he'll be a risky investment in fantasy drafts until his legal issues are sorted.

Parham went undrafted back in 2019 and failed to make a 53-man roster, but the Stetson product eventually made a name for himself with the Dallas Renegades of the XFL. Parham signed with the Chargers after the XFL shut down and went on to post a 10-159-3 receiving line off the bench in 2020. The 24-year-old is on the 2021 fantasy radar after Los Angeles replaced Hunter Henry with 34-year-old Jared Cook. Cook may be the favorite to pace the position in targets, but Parham very well could steal the gig with a strong offseason. The 6-foot-8 Parham is an intriguing deep sleeper in the Chargers' ascending offense.

Dissly is entering his fourth NFL season having occasionally flashed fantasy value, but having also failed to put together a single top-35 fantasy campaign. Injuries limited the 2018 fourth-round pick to eight full games during his first two seasons, though he was good when active, producing at least 13 fantasy points in six of those games. He finally appeared in all 16 games in 2020, but played a situational role as he fully recovered from a torn Achilles and was limited to a 24-251-2 receiving line on 30 targets. Dissly's 7.0 RAC topped the position and his 80% catch rate ranked fifth. Perhaps the 25-year-old will enjoy a breakout in 2021, but he'll need to fend off newcomer Gerald Everett. Dissly should be monitored, but not drafted in most formats.

Graham is entering his 12th NFL season. He's now 34 years old, but remains a reliable player, having appeared in 16 games seven of the past eight seasons. Graham was a weapon near the goal line for Chicago last season, ranking fourth at TE in TDs (eight) and second in end zone targets (12). That allowed a 13th-place finish in fantasy points, though his playing time and targets did dwindle as the team got rookie Cole Kmet work in the second half of the season. Graham handled 6.1 targets per game during his first nine games, but 3.0 per game in the final seven. Graham will hit for the occasional TD, but his days as a consistent target and fantasy TE are likely over. He doesn't need to be drafted.

Hill is the NFL's most versatile player as his unique role in the Saints offense allows him to contribute as a passer, rusher, receiver and on special teams. Last season, Hill attempted 121 passes, racked up 87 carries and was targeted 12 times. Most of the passes came during four starts at QB in place of an injured Drew Brees. Hill showed well, completing 72% of 114 attempts for 834 yards, 4 TDs and 2 INTs while adding 39-209-4 on the ground. Only six QBs scored more fantasy points during the stretch and Hill was top-13 all four weeks. The 30-year-old managed zero top-18 fantasy weeks during the other 12 weeks, so his fantasy appeal rests entirely on whether he beats out Jameis Winston for starting duties. If he does, Hill's legs supply QB1 upside.

Dalton signed with Chicago during free agency and, though he was promised the team's starting job, it won't be long before first-round pick Justin Fields takes over. After spending his first nine seasons with the Bengals, Dalton was uneven as Dak Prescott's injury replacement in Dallas last season. He was the most conservative he's been in his career (6.9 average depth of throw), while tossing 14 TDs and eight INTs. He produced one top-12 fantasy week in nine "full" games and has finished a season better than 12th in fantasy points only once in his career (sixth in 2013). Having Allen Robinson in the fold helps, but 33-year-old Dalton is now a bottom-tier NFL starter with little rushing ability and thus a longshot to come anywhere close to QB1 production.

Lock is entering a make-or-break third season as the starter in Denver. The 2019 second-round pick was aggressive (his 9.3 average depth of throw ranked second), but inefficient (57% catch rate, 6.6 YPA) and inconsistent (four top-8 fantasy weeks, but eight outside the top 20) in his first full season as a starter in 2020. The good news is that the 24-year-old has a good, young supporting cast led by Courtland Sutton, Jerry Jeudy, KJ Hamler, Tim Patrick, Noah Fant, Melvin Gordon and Javonte Williams. Lock is certainly a sleeper for a breakout season, but he doesn't do much with legs, is leading a run-heavy offense and isn't guaranteed to start every game with Teddy Bridgewater in the fold. Lock is a longshot for consistent QB1 numbers.

Minshew is one of the league's most entertaining players and he's certainly a success story relative to his pedigree (2019 sixth-round pick), but he simply hasn't done enough to cement a starting gig in the NFL. His numbers actually aren't too bad - he's thrown 37 TDs to 11 INTs on 797 career attempts and improved his completion rate to 66% in 2020 - but inconsistent and erratic play has led to multiple benchings. In eight starts last season, Minshew showed a high floor (QB12 in fantasy points), but very low ceiling (zero top-10 weeks). The 25-year-old will barely be on the QB2 radar if called on to start in 2021.

Rudolph signed with the Giants after 10 seasons with the Vikings. The 2011 second-round pick was reduced to 3.2 targets per game last season, which was his lowest usage since his rookie season. Rudolph also missed his first game action since 2014, sitting out the final four weeks due to a foot injury. The result? A 28-334-1 receiving line and career-worst 39th-place finish in fantasy points. The 31-year-old likely has a few good years left, but he does not have a path to consistent targets with Evan Engram ahead of him on the depth chart in a New York offense that also added Kenny Golladay and Kadarius Toney. Rudolph is a reliable set of hands and will score the occasional TD, but he's unlikely to provide consistent TE2 numbers.

Freiermuth was selected by Pittsburgh with the 55th-overall pick of April's draft. The Penn State product is a big, strong and athletic 6-foot-5, 258-pound TE who can help as a blocker and receiver. Granted it was only four games, but he handled a massive 29% target share (30% air yard share) in 2020. Freiermuth isn't especially fast or agile and his hands are inconsistent, but he's good with the ball in his hands has the skills to eventually push for TE1 numbers. Of course, there's a learning curve for rookie TEs and, at least in 2021, he's positioned as Pittsburgh's replacement for the retired Vance McDonald as a secondary option behind Eric Ebron. Freiermuth has little to no short-term fantasy value and is only worth drafting in dynasty leagues.

Herndon was a popular sleeper during 2020 fantasy drafts, but the 2018 fourth-round pick disappointed in Adam Gase's offense as so many have before him. Herndon flashed with a 39-502-4 receiving line and terrific efficiency as a rookie before missing all but one game due to injury in 2019. Despite playing 68% of the Jets' snaps last season, he was held to a 31-287-3 receiving line, though he did finish strong with a 11-97-2 receiving line on 14 targets during Weeks 16-17 (he was fantasy TE2 during the stretch). With a new coach and QB in place, perhaps the 25-year-old can get back on track in 2021, but he's only worth a late flier in deep leagues.

Alie-Cox was on the field for a career-high 45% of the offensive snaps last season, but couldn't emerge as a legitimate fantasy option in the merry-go-round that was the Colts' tight end room. Alie-Cox posted a 31-394-2 receiving line in 16 games, though 8-161-1 of that came in two early-season games. Alie-Cox's efficiency was good, as the 2017 UDFA ranked no lower than sixth in catch rate, YPT and RAC. In seven seasons, coach Frank Reich has never had a TE unit fall below a 23% target share (27% average), but that was the case in 2020 when Alie-Cox only handled 7% of the targets. The 27-year-old will compete with Jack Doyle and rookie Kylen Granson for snaps this season and is a longshot to join the TE1 discussion.

Bryant returns as a situational player in Cleveland after a solid rookie campaign. Despite the presence of Austin Hooper and David Njoku, Bryant was on the field for 59% of Cleveland’s offensive snaps during 15 regular season games. The fourth-round pick out of Florida Atlantic posted a 24-238-3 receiving line and that included a 4-56-2 showing in place of an injured Hooper in Week 7. Bryant will remain in a similar role this season as he’s set to battle Njoku for work behind Hooper. The 23-year-old has no standalone value, but would be worth a speculative add if Hooper were to miss time.

Njoku has yet to live up to his first round pedigree and is set to enter his fifth NFL season as a backup/situational player in Cleveland. The 25-year-old missed three games last season and was limited to 49% of the snaps and 2.2 targets per game when active. After missing all but four games in 2019, Njoku has a total of 24 receptions for 254 yards and three TDs over the past two seasons. That’s a far cry from his 56-639-4 receiving line and ninth-place finish in fantasy points back in 2018. Njoku’s only shot at consistent fantasy value is an Austin Hooper injury and even then he’d need to beat out Harrison Bryant for targets. Njoku belongs on waivers.

The Texans selected Mills in the third round of April’s draft. The Stanford product has pedigree (he was the consensus top QB out of high school in 2017) and excellent size (6-foot-4, 222 pounds) to go along with good accuracy and a strong arm. The problem? A lack of experience. Mills made a grand total of 11 starts during four seasons with the Cardinal, tossing 18 TDs and 8 INTs on 438 attempts while adding little with his legs. A developmental period would be ideal, but it’s possible he'll makes some starts in 2021 if Deshaun Watson is not cleared to play. Mills will open his career behind Tyrod Taylor and doesn’t need to be drafted, but keep him on your watch list in superflex leagues.

Mariota returns to Las Vegas as Derek Carr's primary backup. Mariota was limited to one appearance in 2020 and showed well with 226 passing yards, 88 rushing yards and a pair of TDs in a Week 15 game against the Chargers. Of course, prior to that, the 2015 second-overall pick struggled during five seasons in Tennessee. The Oregon product has been effective with his legs throughout his career (251-1487-12 career rushing line), but that has yet to translate to a top-12 fantasy campaign (he's finished better than 18th once). Mariota will leap into the QB2 discussion if called on to replace the underrated Carr, but the 27-year-old is well off the fantasy radar in the meantime.

Brissett signed with Miami during the offseason and will back up Tua Tagovailoa. Brissett started for the Colts in place of Andrew Luck in 2017 and 2019, but has otherwise been relegated to backup duties. The 2016 third-round pick has struggled with passing efficiency (career 60% completion rate and 6.6 YPA), but does add a little bit of value with his legs (top-10 in carries and TDs at QB in both seasons as a starter). Brissett finished 26th in fantasy points per game in 2017 and 2019 and, despite what is shaping up to be a good supporting cast in Miami, the 28-year-old is a longshot for anything more than back-end QB2 numbers if called on to replace unproven Tagovailoa.

Trubisky's time in Chicago has come and gone and the 2017 second-overall pick is now Josh Allen's backup in Buffalo. Trubisky took a step forward in his second pro season in 2018, but has since regressed. In 2020, Trubisky was benched in the third game of the season and then later reinstated as starter, playing the bulk of the snaps in eight games. His play was all over the map, as he produced four top-10 fantasy weeks, and four of 23rd or worse. In total, he was QB14 those eight weeks. With the Bills' pass-heavy offense in mind, the 27-year-old will only be worth a flier if Allen misses time with an injury.

Love is entering his second NFL season after the Packers traded up to select him with the 26th overall pick of the 2020 draft. Love made some recent history by becoming the only first-round rookie QB in the past decade to not play a single snap in his rookie season. Love is obviously a major unknown and we haven't seen him play at a high level since 2018. He struggled in his final season at Utah State in 2019, as he tossed 20 TDs to 17 INTs and his off-target rate (15.5) and QBR (51.7) were both worst of last year's rookie class. Love has a good arm, but his struggles with accuracy, turnovers and decision-making are concerns. There's long-term upside, but Love is only on the fantasy radar because of Aaron Rodgers' uncertain future in Green Bay. Unless Rodgers is traded, Love does not need to be drafted.

Trask was selected by Tampa Bay with the 64th overall pick of April's draft. The former Gator is a big quarterback at 6-foot-5, 236 pounds and is also one of the older (23) prospects in this year's QB class. Trask improved throughout his time at Florida and has a solid arm, but his accuracy has been inconsistent and he benefited from a terrific supporting cast. Trask did pace this year's QB class in pass TDs in 2020 (43) and his efficiency numbers were solid, but his lack of mobility will be problematic for his fantasy outlook (54 rushing yards during two full seasons). As long as Tom Brady is on the roster, Trask will only be worth a stash in dynasty leagues.
